ENTRY            14860   20260115   20260316   20260316       1526
SUBENT        14860001   20260115   20260316   20260316       1526
BIB                  8         28
TITLE      Gamma-ray pulse-height response of an NE-213
           scintillation detector
AUTHOR     (D.T.Ingersoll,B.W.Wehring)
REFERENCE  (J,NIM,147,551,1977)
           #doi:10.1016/0029-554X(77)90401-3
INSTITUTE  (1USAUI)
FACILITY   (MICRT,1USAUI) The UIUC superconducting electron
           microtron.
DETECTOR   (SCIN) A 5 cm by 5 cm NE-213 organic scintillation
           detector. The glass bottle is connected with a 0.62
           cm light pipe to an Amperex 56AVP photomultiplier
           tube. The scintillator is covered with a
           loose-fitting aluminum foil reflector and wrapped in
           black plastic tape.
METHOD     (GSPEC,PSD) In order to use an NE-213 detector as a
           gamma ray spectrometer, it was necessary to accurately
           determine the response of the detector. Monoenergetic
           gamma-ray sources were provided for this purpose at
           low energies by radioisotopes and at higher energies
           with a bremsstrahlung monochromator which provided
           over 100 monoenergetic gamma-ray sources between 2
           and 11.5 MeV. Gamma-ray response functions were
           deduced for an NE-213 scintillation detector, and a
           measurement was made of the 252Cf total gamma-ray
           spectrum. Pulse-shape discrimination was used to
           eliminate neutrons and a Pb shadow bar was used to
           measure background.
HISTORY    (20260115C) BP
